[DONE] JIT hardening + loop-coverage expansion (2026-06-01, macOS arm64 /
       Darwin 25, both backends; amd64 cross-checked under x86_64 Rosetta).
       Commits 5dd4bfb..da47df6. Five pieces:
       1. REGRESSION FIX: for_loop_inc (forsum) silently stopped JITting after
          commit 997ffbb named let/for slots — OP_BIND_SLOT (2B) became
          OP_BIND_SLOT_NAMED (3B), growing the body 48->50 and shifting every
          hardcoded c[N] offset; both backends were gated on ncode==48 +
          OP_BIND_SLOT, so forsum dropped to the VM (no test failure, only a
          ~78x arm64 / ~159x amd64 benchmark slowdown). Re-pointed both
          matchers at the 50-byte layout; forsum re-JITs.
       2. CURSOR MATCHERS: root-caused the above to hardcoded byte offsets.
          Added bc_oplen (length-only twin of bc_disasm_one — KEEP IN LOCKSTEP)
          + BC_TAKE/BC_EAT/BC_TAKE_ANY/BC_EAT_ANY/BC_END/BC_ARG/BC_I16 in
          jit_common.h, and converted ALL 26 shape matchers on both backends to
          walk the bytecode by real opcode lengths instead of c[N] literals.
          Offset drift can no longer silently mis-match a shape. Emitted machine
          code unchanged throughout (parse-only refactor).
       3. WIDER LOOP JIT: (a) generalized arm64 simple_tail_loop to materialize
          a wide/negative tagged compare limit into a reg (was capped at u12 →
          limit<=511), so count-up loops to any i16 limit JIT; (b) new
          try_jit_wide_counter_loop (both backends) for counter loops whose
          const limit exceeds i16 (the generic LOAD_SLOT/LOAD_CONST/<cmp>
          triple, not the fused SLOT_<cmp>_FIX) — e.g. (if (< n 5000000) ...);
          (c) new predicate-gated cons loop (sieve primes-up-to): first shape
          with a value-returning global call per iteration + a heap cons, done
          as a 4-instruction trampoline tail-calling a shared C kernel
          (jit_predicate_cons_loop, jit_common.h) rather than risky hand-emitted
          loop/cons/refcount machine code — resolves the predicate via the
          gcache/lookup the call trampolines use, conses with jit_build_inc_cons's
          refcount discipline. ~18x faster than the VM, RSS-flat (no leak).
       4. TESTS: self-gating JIT-coverage block in test.alc (asserts (jit? f)
          for every shape; build-independent so the assert count matches across
          JIT and non-JIT variants — the net that would have caught forsum) +
          jit_fuzz.py / `make jit-fuzz`: a differential fuzzer that runs
          randomized counter/leaf/float-acc shapes under a JIT and a non-JIT
          build, asserting byte-identical jit==VM (msgpack type+bit exact) AND
          100% shape coverage.
       5. New tail-call encoders arm64_br / x64_jmp_reg verified byte-identical
          vs the system assembler. VALIDATION: test-all ALL VARIANTS PASSED
          (alcove 1401/0 x5, adder 1407/0 x5, wasm 160+28); arm64 fuzz ~650
          results byte-identical at 100% coverage; amd64 1383/0 (no-FFI) under
          Rosetta; ASan-clean. NOT done: predicate-cons is shape-pinned to
          slots i=0,n=1,acc=2 / const 0 (the sieve driver); a fully general
          dual-tail emitter is future.

[DONE] arm64 (Apple Silicon) JIT for the scalar FLOAT-accumulator loop
       (2026-05-31, macOS arm64 / Darwin 25, clang -O3, commit 930ae43).
       try_jit_float_acc_loop ported into the arm64 backend (jit_arm64.h) as a
       faithful NEON mirror of the amd64 fn (commit 23c0fc4); both backends now
       at parity for this shape. Wired into jit_compile right after
       simple_tail_loop (same order as amd64).
       IMPL: tagged counter in x1, UNBOXED accumulator in d0, float const in
         d1, tagged limit materialized in x4 (no amd64 imm32 ceiling → any
         61-bit fixnum limit JITs). fadd/fsub/fmul (double); scvtf coerces an
         int seed; the float seed loads from box->f behind a tag(0)/non-null/
         type==EXP_FLOAT guard. env held in callee-saved x19 across the two
         exit callouts; loop folds to one b.cond back-edge (no per-iter
         callout). Static gate copied exactly (isnumber(lim) && isfloat(fc)).
         0-iter returns refexp(seed) UNCHANGED (int stays int, float stays
         float — no spurious box); >=1-iter boxes d0 once via make_floatf.
         Guards run before any slot mutation; deopt (NULL) re-runs the VM on an
         untouched env. Added the scalar-double NEON encoders the shape needs
         (ldr d, fmov d<-x, scvtf, fadd/fsub/fmul) + ldrh + and-#7; all verified
         byte-identical against the system assembler. Step delta limited to a
         u12 (only +1-style steps JIT; anything else deopts — VM stays correct).
       VALIDATION (all green): (a) make test-all ALL VARIANTS PASSED — alcove
         1366/0 x5 + adder 1154/0 x5 + wasm 74+10; fib/fact/ack/tak/nqueens
         still pass (existing arm64 shapes intact). (b) ASan+UBSan run of
         test.alc clean (1348/0 = 1366 − 18 FFI on the no-FFI build), zero
         hits, + a 1.8M-call float-loop churn over every path (int/float/neg
         seed, mul, 0-iter int & float) with flat RSS. (c) jit-vs-nojit
         BYTE-IDENTICAL (msgpack-encoded, type+bit-exact) across add/sub/mul x
         {int,float seed} x {neg,zero,large} + 0-iter passthrough. (d) 30M-iter
         loop ~28x faster than the VM (amd64 saw ~37x). (e) the "facc"/
         "bm-faccadd" asserts in test.alc are green and now exercise the arm64
         JIT. The real emitted machine code was disassembled and audited
         instruction by instruction (JIT confirmed via TIMING, not the
         unreliable disasm jit-status line).
       REF: amd64 impl jit_amd64.h::try_jit_float_acc_loop (commit 23c0fc4);
         OP_SLOT_IS_FIX two-backend lockstep (commit 0f62963) was the model.

[DONE] LINUX/amd64 RUNTIME VERIFICATION (2026-05-29, Debian 13 / kernel
       6.12, x86_64, gcc, libffi 3.4.8 + libreadline). The 2026-05 feature
       work (FFI callbacks/struct-by-value/varargs/nested structs + the ""
       self-library, HAMT, call/cc, MessagePack) is now RUN-verified on
       Linux/amd64, not just macOS arm64. Results:
       1. `make test-all` → 1069 passed, 0 failed on ALL 10 variants
          (5 alcove + 5 adder; FFI + readline detected).
       2. ASan: initially flagged a 527-byte leak (19 strdup allocs) — the
          savedb/loaddb path-adoption strdup that overwrote alcove_db_path
          without freeing the prior owned copy (a long-acknowledged "leaks
          rarely" comment). FIXED via alcove_set_db_path() + an ownership
          flag (frees the previous heap copy; never frees the literal/argv
          default). Re-run: 1069/0, ZERO AddressSanitizer reports (errors
          AND leaks). No heap-overflow/UAF anywhere.
       3. amd64 JIT auto-selected on x86_64: fib 25=75025, fib 32=2178309,
          full benchmark suite runs JIT'd (ackermann 95x python, fact 29x).
          (disasm fib) → "jit installed (4096 byte mmap page)" and the fn
          executes correctly → the non-Apple W^X RW→mprotect(R+X) path is
          accepted by this kernel.
       4. ffi-examples 01-07 all clean: 05 callbacks 42/285/21/1000;
          06 struct-by-value norm2(3,4)=25, seg-len2=25 (SysV ABI);
          07 varargs printf "int=42 str=hello float=3.50", returned 30.
       5. "" self-library (dlopen(NULL) + -rdynamic): (ffi-fn "" "strlen"
          ...) bound and called → "abc"=3, "hello, world"=12. (Note: `it`
          isn't an alcove REPL binding; used (= slen (ffi-fn ...)) instead.)
       6. RESP server (-r): PING/SET/GET/INCR, 500KB value STRLEN=500000.
          Slow-reader flood (~120MB queued into a non-reading socket): server
          survived, PING returned PONG after — write-buffer ceiling /
          wfail-drop hardening holds, no crash.
       7. qemu-aarch64 cross-check: aarch64-linux-gnu-gcc -DALCOVE_JIT=1
          (no FFI) → 1051 passed, 0 failed (= 1069 − ~18 FFI block, as
          predicted); fib 25=75025 with "jit installed" → arm64 JIT works
          under emulation.

